column1: Who will win Georgia's 6th Congressional district in the upcoming special election?
column6: ['Elections and Referenda']
column11: Thanks to aggressive spending by both parties, the race for Georgia's 6th district has become the most expensive congressional election in history. Early voting for the contest started May 30th and will be open through June 16. (The Hill) The election is scheduled to conclude on June 20th. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: The race to succeed Tom Price, now the health secretary, as representative for Georgia’s 6th district has been the costliest in congressional history. The run-off election today pits Jon Ossoff, a 30-year-old documentary film-maker and former Democratic congressional aide, against Karen Handel, a veteran Georgia Republican. The contest has been supercharged by tens of millions of dollars in spending, much of it by outside groups who see it as a test of the parties’ prospects in the age of President Donald Trump. Oddly, neither candidate has been outspoken about the president, for fear of riling swing voters. The district, a stretch of mostly well-heeled Atlanta suburbs, was for decades safe Republican territory, but in November Mr Trump took it only by a whisker. Mr Ossoff narrowly missed an outright win in the poll’s first round, in April—but then the Republican field was crowded. Today’s contest will be close

In Georgia, voters will go to the polls to decide whether Republican Karen Handel or Democrat Jon Ossoff will represent the 6th Congressional District in the U.S. House. The runoff election, which has become the most expensive U.S. House race in history, has garnered national attention. In the 18-candidate special election on April 18, Ossoff received 48 percent of the vote against Handel's runner-up total of 19.8 percent. Votes for Republican candidates, however, slightly outpaced votes for Democratic candidates, 51 to 49 percent. The special election became necessary when Tom Price (R) was confirmed to become the Secretary of Health and Human Services. Georgia's 6th Congressional District has been held by a Republican continuously since Newt Gingrich took the seat in 1979, but the district voted for President Trump (R) over Democrat Hillary Clinton by a margin of just 1.5 percentage points in 2016. Polling has shown a tight race, indicating something between a tie race and a 7 percentage point advantage for Ossoff over the past month.- Ballotpedia

I couldn't find the numbers with regard to party registration to establish my baseline for the 6th District. So I'll have to go with what's election results. In Nov 2016, Tom Price won the district by the margin of 23.3% (201,088 vs. 124,917). Meanwhile, Trump only won the district by 1.6% (often cited number, I don't have concrete number). Assuming people vote in November vote for both presidential and congress, and remove 3% Gary Johnson votes, there would be 47.7% Clinton, 49.3% Trump. That tells me 40,300 Republicans (or 12.3% of all voters) who voted for Tom Price crossed over to vote for Clinton as a protest vote against Trump. The protest votes are already baked into the November number. These protest votes continue to maintain its proportion in the April Special Election: Ossoff has 48.3% of the votes.

Averaging polls from https://goo.gl/eEt2a6, Ossoff's average during runoff is 48% to Handel's 46%; for past 30 days that increases to 50/46, respectively. HuffPost and RealClearPolitics have the averages at 50.9/44 and 49.8/45, respectively. However, I don't see any polls where that difference is outside the MOE. Thus, it seems like Ossoff has a softish lead, especially considering that the special election polls near the election underestimated Ossoff by 6 points (https://goo.gl/ttjvp8).

I believe the preponderance of voters who will turn out will be anti-trump, not pro-Democrat. It will be difficult to retain the seat in 2018 if Ossoff wins, but a special election, even with the massive efforts on both sides, always has a low turnout.

If this election is a referendum on Trump, Dems would do well not to overestimate their chances (see November 2016). As we saw last year, polling is only so effective, and requires a participant who wants to answer the pollsters questions. Right now, it is not surprising that those opposed to Trump are more vocal than those who support Trump. But this is a gerrymandered district with a solid Rep base, and it's important to keep in mind that the drama of Trump inside the beltway doesn't necessarily equate to decreased support outside the beltway.

The election seems to be, in part, a referendum on Trump. Trump's standing appears to be increasingly damaged significantly by the Russia investigations -- even among Repubs, independents, those who voted for Trump because they felt Hillary was also a problematic candidate.
